Thought: I inspected the focal claim in initial_details.txt, the structured information in post_registration.json, the provided replication dataset (Final replication dataset.rds) and the “Replication attempt code (FINAL).R”.  
•  The replication dataset contains 20 026 student-level observations from 11 European countries with English achievement plausible values (writing, reading, listening) and all background variables used in the original ELEMENT study (age, gender, SES/HISEI, parental education, cultural-capital books, home-language items to construct a bilingual dummy).  
•  The R script already reproduces the analytic strategy: exclusion of students speaking English at home, construction of a bilingual indicator, derivation of an averaged English-achievement score, centring / standardising controls, and fitting a three-level mixed-effects model (students ⟶ schools ⟶ countries) using lmerTest.  
•  Compared with the original ELEMENT data (Grade-6 German sample) this ESLC dataset supplies an independent sample (different countries, older grade, distinct assessment instrument) but maintains high fidelity to the theoretical construct (English foreign-language achievement vs bilingual home background with the same socio-demographic covariates). Therefore it is appropriate for a robustness replication.

